ofane -- tChapter Ten “Tossing the Flower for the Sake of the Divinities”: Kechien Kanjō and the Medieval Japanese Cosmology -- tChapter Eleven Ritually Embodying the Lotus Sutra: An Interpretation of the Japanese Tendai Kurodani Lineage Consecrated Ordination (Kai Kanjō) -- tChapter Twelve The Abhiṣeka of the Yogin: Bodily Practices and the Interiorization of Ritual in Medieval Japan -- tChapter Thirteen The World of Shintō Kanjō, With a Focus on Ryōbu Shinto -- tChapter Fourteen The Consecration of Acolytes (Chigo Kanjō): Ritualizing Male-Male Sexuality in Medieval Tendai -- tChapter Fifteen Before the Appearance of Shugen Kanjō: Origin and History of a Forged Ritual -- tChapter Sixteen Buchū Kanjō: Secret Dharma Transmission in the Shugendō Mountain-Entry Ritual -- tPart Four: Developments in the Arts -- tChapter Seventeen Kokin Kanjō: Rituals and Conceptualizations -- tChapter Eighteen The Consecration to the Art of the Biwa (Biwa Kanjō) -- tChapter Nineteen Shō kanjō: Music Education, Secret Melodies, and Imperial Politics -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn premodern Japan, legitimization of power and knowledge in various contexts was sanctioned by consecration rituals (kanjō) of Buddhist origin. This is the first book to address in a comprehensive way the multiple forms and aspects of these rituals also in relation to other Asian contexts.The multidisciplinary chapters in the book address the origins of these rituals in ancient Persia and India and their developments in China and Tibet, before discussing in depth their transformations in medieval Japan. In particular, kanjō rituals are examined from various perspectives: imperial ceremonies, Buddhist monastic rituals, vernacular religious forms (Shugendō mountain cults, Shinto lineages), rituals of bodily transformation involving sexual practice, and the performing arts: a history of these developments, descriptions of actual rituals, and reference to religious and intellectual arguments based on under-examined primary sources. No other book presents so many cases of kanjō in such depth and breadth.This book is relevant to readers interested in Buddhist studies, Japanese religions, the history of Japanese culture, and in the intersections between religious doctrines, rituals, legitimization, and performance.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aBuddhist templesxDedicationzJapanxHistory. 4aAsiatische Religionen. 4aBuddhismus. 4aJapan. 4aRituale. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / Rituals & Practice.2bisacsh  aAsian religions.  aBuddhism.  aJapan.  arituals.1 aAbé, Ryūichi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastiglioni, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChihiro, Inose, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDolce, Lucia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroner, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIkuyo, Matsumoto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeisuke, Unno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Susan Blakeley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrug, Adam C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMasahide, Mori, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPorath, Or, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPorath, Or, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRambelli, Fabio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRambelli, Fabio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocab